<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{mo}}</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

<body>

<h1>@HI{{mo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<p>
<dl>
<dt> (A) "also, too"
<ol>
<li> @N1{{}} @HI{{ha}} ... @N2{{}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>
</ol>
<dt> (B) "both, as well"
<ol>
<li> @N1{{}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> @N2{{}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>
</ol>
<dt> (C) "as much as, as many as"
<ol>
<li> number/counter <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>
</ol>
</dl>
</p>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
In sentence pattern (A) a topic is introduced in the first utterance and in a subsequent sentence
<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> is used to increase the scope of the topic.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{kurara}}@HI{{sanha}}@KJ{{England}}@KJ{{word}}@HI{{ga}} @KJ{{tale}}@HI{{semasu.}}
      @KT{{furansu}}@KJ{{word}}<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> @KJ{{tale}}@HI{{semasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Klara can speak English. She can speak French too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
In sentence pattern (B) @N1{{}} and @N2{{}} are introduced as topics in parallel.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{flower^child}}sanha sushi<strong>mo</strong>tenpura<strong>mo</strong>@KJ{{fond}}kidesuyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Hanako likes both sushi and tempura.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
In sentence pattern (C) <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> follows a number or a counter to express the
idea that the speaker believes that the amount or number mentioned is large.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> can indicate an addition such as "as well as".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{koreha@KJ{{black}}desukara,@KJ{{white}}i@KJ{{shoes}}<strong>mo</strong>arimasuyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      These are black but we have white shoes as well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> can be used to show emphasis about a time or quantity.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}ha@KJ{{what^degrees}}<strong>mo</strong>@KJ{{see}}mashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I've seen that film any number of times.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{sumisu}}sanha @KJ{{sino-^character}}wo5000<strong>mo</strong>@KJ{{know}}tteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Smith knows as many as 5000 kanji.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> can be used to indicate a total negation when used with a negative verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{section^roof}}niha,dare<strong>mo</strong>imasenyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There is noone in that room.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> can be used to indicate an approximation.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{1@KJ{{time^interval}}<strong>mo</strong>areba,@KT{{hoteru}}kara@KJ{{empty^harbor}}he@KJ{{going}}kemasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You can get from the hotel to the airport in an hour or so.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}}, <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>
replaces those particles. For all other particles, <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong> follows them rather than
replacing them.
</p>

